The '''250t-class''' were high-seas [[torpedo boat]]s built for the [[Austro-Hungarian Navy]] in 1913<U+2013>16. A total of 27 boats were built by three shipbuilding companies, with the letter after the boat number indicating the manufacturer. There were small variations between manufacturers, mainly in the [[steam turbine]]s used, and whether they had one or two [[funnel (ship)|funnels]]. The eight boats of the T-group, designated ''74 T''&nbsp;<U+2013>&nbsp;''81 T'', were built by [[Stabilimento Tecnico Triestino]], located at [[Trieste]]. The sixteen boats of the F-group, designated ''82 F''&nbsp;<U+2013>&nbsp;''97 F'', were built by [[Ganz Works|Ganz & Danubius]] at their shipyards at [[Rijeka|Fiume]] and [[Kraljevica|Porto Re]]. The three M-group boats, designated ''98&nbsp;M''&nbsp;<U+2013>&nbsp;''100&nbsp;M'', were manufactured by [[Cantiere Navale Triestino]] at [[Monfalcone]].

All 27 boats saw service in [[World War I]], performing [[convoy]], escort and [[minesweeping]] tasks, and [[Anti-submarine warfare|anti-submarine operations]], but none were lost. In 1917, one of the {{convert|66|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns on each boat was placed on an [[anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft]] mount. Under the terms of the [[Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (1919)|Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye]], the boats were transferred to various countries, including seven to [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]], six to [[First Portuguese Republic|Portugal]], six to [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]], and eight to the newly created [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] (later Yugoslavia). By 1940, thirteen boats of the class had been lost or [[Ship breaking|scrapped]], including all six Portuguese boats.

During [[World War II]], the five remaining Greek boats were sunk by [[Nazi Germany|German]] aircraft during the [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[Battle of Greece|invasion of Greece]] in April 1941. The six surviving Yugoslav boats were captured by the [[Kingdom of Italy|Italians]] during the Axis [[invasion of Yugoslavia]] in April 1941, and were operated by the ''[[Regia Marina]]''. Immediately following the Italian [[Armistice of Cassibile|capitulation]] in September 1943, one ex-Yugoslav boat was sunk by German aircraft, another was [[Scuttling|scuttled]] by its Italian crew, and a third fell into [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] hands. The rest were seized by the Germans. Of these, two were handed over to the [[Navy of the Independent State of Croatia]], one of which was destroyed by [[Royal Navy]] [[Motor Torpedo Boat]]s in 1944. The other was transferred to the [[Yugoslav Navy]] after World War II and continued to serve until 1959, when she was taken out of service. Another was operated by the [[Kriegsmarine|German Navy]] ({{lang-de|Kriegsmarine}}) with a Croatian crew until she was sunk by [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft in 1945. The surviving Croatian boat was handed over to the Yugoslav Navy after the war and served until 1963. The remaining Romanian boat performed escort tasks in the [[Black Sea]] before being taken over by the [[Soviet Navy]], and serving in their [[Black Sea Fleet]] until the end of the war; it was finally scrapped in 1958.

==Background==
In 1910, the [[Austria-Hungary]] Naval Technical Committee initiated the design and development of a {{convert|275|t|LT|0|adj=on}} coastal [[torpedo boat]], specifying that it should be capable of sustaining {{convert|30|kn|link=in}} for 10 hours. This specification was based an expectation that the [[Strait of Otranto]], where the [[Adriatic Sea]] meets the [[Ionian Sea]], would be [[blockade]]d by hostile forces during a future conflict. In such circumstances, there would be a need for a torpedo boat that could sail from the [[Austro-Hungarian Navy]] base at [[Kotor|Cattaro]] to the Strait during darkness, locate and attack blockading ships and return to port before morning. [[Steam turbine]] power was selected for propulsion, as [[Marine propulsion#Reciprocating diesel engines|diesels]] with the necessary power were not available, and the Austro-Hungarian Navy did not have the practical experience to run [[Turbo-electric transmission|turbo-electric]] boats.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}}

==Description and construction==
[[Stabilimento Tecnico Triestino]] (STT) of [[Trieste]] was selected for the contract to build eight vessels, ahead of one other tenderer. Despite the specifications of the contract being very close to the requirements for the coastal torpedo boat, the STT boats were classified as sea-going.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}} The STT boats used [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] turbines.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=58}} Another tender was requested for four more boats, but when [[Ganz Works|Ganz & Danubius]] reduced their price by ten percent, a total of sixteen boats were ordered from them. These boats were powered by [[AEG]]-Curtiss turbines, and had two [[Funnel (ship)|funnels]] rather than the single funnel of the STT boats.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}} The third contract went to [[Cantiere Navale Triestino]] (CNT), who used Melms-Pfenniger turbines, and their boats also had two funnels.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=63}} The boats of all three groups used steam generated by two [[Yarrow Shipbuilders|Yarrow]] [[water-tube boiler]]s, one of which burned [[fuel oil]] and the other coal.{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58, 60 & 63}}

When completed, all 27 boats were armed with two [[<U+0160>koda Works|<U+0160>koda]] {{convert|66|mm|in|abbr=on}} L/30{{refn|L/30 denotes the length of the gun. In this case, the L/30 gun is 30 [[Caliber (artillery)|calibre]], meaning that the gun was 30 times as long as the diameter of its bore.|group = lower-alpha}} guns, and four {{convert|450|mm|in|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tubes]]. Each vessel could carry 10<U+2013>12 [[naval mine]]s.{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58, 60 & 63}}{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=10}}

===T-group===
The T-group were built by STT at the [[Port of Trieste]] between April 1913 and December 1914. They had a [[waterline length]] of {{convert|58.2|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|5.7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, and a normal [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|1.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. While their designed displacement was {{convert|262|t|LT|0}}, they displaced about {{convert|320|t|LT}} fully loaded. The crew consisted of 39 officers and enlisted men. Their Parsons turbines were rated at {{convert|5000|shp|lk=in|abbr=on}} with a maximum output of {{convert|6000|shp|lk=no|abbr=on}} and designed to reach a top speed of {{convert|28|kn}}.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=58}} They carried {{convert|18|t|LT}} of coal and {{convert|24|t|LT}} of fuel oil,{{sfn|Jane's Information Group|1989|p=313}} which gave them a range of {{convert|980|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|16|kn}}.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=58}}

The T-group boats were originally to be armed with three {{convert|66|mm|in|abbr=on}} L/30 guns, and three {{convert|450|mm|in|abbr=on}} torpedo tubes,{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}} but this was changed to two guns and four torpedo tubes before the first boat was completed,{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=58}} in order to standardise the armament with the following F-group. In 1914, one {{convert|8|mm|in|abbr=on}} [[machine gun]] was added.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}}
