When ''74 T'''s turbines were initially installed, the problems with them were so significant that all her power and propulsion machinery had to be rebuilt. She was launched for a second time on 26 June 1914.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=58}}

===F-group===
The F-group were built by Ganz & Danubius at [[Rijeka|Fiume]] and nearby [[Kraljevica|Porto Re]] between October 1913 and December 1916. They had a waterline length of {{convert|58.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a beam of {{convert|5.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, and a normal draught of {{convert|1.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. While their designed displacement was {{convert|266|t|LT|0}}, they displaced about {{convert|330|t|LT}} fully loaded.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=58}} The crew consisted of 38 officers and enlisted men. Their AEG-Curtiss turbines were rated at {{convert|5000|shp|lk=no|abbr=on}} with a maximum output of {{convert|6000|shp|lk=no|abbr=on}}, and the boats were designed to reach a top speed of {{convert|28|kn}}. During trials, ''93 F'' produced {{convert|6450|shp|lk=no|abbr=on}}, and reached a top speed of {{convert|29.7|kn}}. They carried {{convert|20|LT}} of coal and {{convert|34|LT}} of fuel oil,{{sfn|Jane's Information Group|1989|p=313}} which gave them a range of {{convert|1200|nmi|lk=no|abbr=on}} at {{convert|16|kn}}.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=60}}
