===World War II===
By 1940, thirteen boats of the class had been lost or scrapped, including all six Portuguese boats.{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58, 60 & 63}} At the time of the [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[Balkan Campaign (World War II)|Balkan Campaign]] of April 1941, ''T1'' and ''T3'' were assigned to the Southern Sector of Coastal Defence Command based at the Bay of Kotor, along with several [[minesweeper]]s and other craft.{{sfn|Niehorster|2013a}} ''T5''<U+2013>''T8'' comprised the 3rd Torpedo Division located at [[<U+0160>ibenik]].{{sfn|Niehorster|2013b}} On 8 April, the four boats of the 3rd Torpedo Division, along with other vessels, were tasked to support an attack on the Italian enclave of [[Zadar]] on the Dalmatia coast. They were subjected to three Italian air attacks and, after the last one, sailed from the area of [[Zaton, Zadar County|Zaton]] into [[Lake Prokljan]], where they remained until 11 April.{{sfn|Terzi<U+0107>|1982|p=333}} On 12 April, the 3rd Torpedo Division arrived at [[Milna]] on the island of [[Bra<U+010D>]], and refused to follow orders to sail to the Bay of Kotor.{{sfn|Terzi<U+0107>|1982|p=404}} All six Yugoslav boats still in service were captured by the Italians during the [[Nazi Germany|German]]-led Axis [[invasion of Yugoslavia]].{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58 & 60}}

The five surviving Greek boats were all sunk by aircraft during the [[Battle of Greece|Axis invasion of Greece]], also in April 1941. The first was ''Proussa'', which was sunk off Corfu on 4 April by Italian [[Junkers Ju 87]] "Picchiatello"s of the 239th Squadron, 97th Dive Bomber Group.{{sfn|Weal|1998|p=22}} Later, ''Kios'' was sunk off [[Athens]] on 22 April, ''Kyzikos'' at [[Salamis Naval Base|Salamis]] on 24 April, ''Pergamos'' off Salamis on 25 April, and ''Kidoniai'' south of the [[Peloponnese]] peninsula on the following day.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=63}}

The three Romanian boats were initially deployed against the [[Soviet Navy]] [[Black Sea Fleet]] following the launch of [[Operation Barbarossa]] in June 1941,{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58, 60 & 63}} with ''Naluca'' and ''Sborul'' allocated to the 3rd Section of the [[Romanian Naval Forces|Romanian Navy]]. On 9 July 1941, ''Naluca'', along with a [[gunboat]] and three [[Motor Torpedo Boat]]s (MTBs), sank the Soviet submarine ''SC-206'' off the southern Romanian coast near [[Mangalia]].{{sfn|Smillie|2012|p=134}} Between 7<U+2013>16 October 1941, all three Romanian torpedo boats were part of the escort for a minelaying group that laid several minefields along the Bulgarian coast to protect Axis shipping.{{sfn|Smillie|2012|p=324}} ''Naluca'' was sunk by Soviet aircraft at [[Constan<U+021B>a]] on 20 August 1944, but ''Sborul'' and ''Smeul'' survived World War II,{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58 & 60}} having been transferred to the Soviet Black Sea Fleet in late August 1944 after Romania changed sides and joined the Allies, serving as ''Musson'' and ''Toros'' respectively.{{sfn|Monakov|Rohwer|2012|pp=167 & 171}}

The Yugoslav boats served with the [[Regia Marina|Royal Italian Navy]] ({{lang-it|Regia Marina}}) under their Yugoslav designations. ''T3'' and ''T5'' were fitted with two {{convert|76|mm|in|abbr=on}} L/30 anti-aircraft guns in place of their {{convert|66|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns, but no other significant alterations were made to them.{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=304}} When the Italians [[Armistice of Cassibile|capitulated]] in September 1943, the Germans seized ''T1'' and transferred her to the [[Navy of the Independent State of Croatia]]. She was renamed ''Gole<U+0161>nica'' and continued in Croatian service until the end of the war. ''T3'' was seized by the Germans at Rijeka and was renamed ''TA48''. During her time in German service she was crewed exclusively by Croatian officers and sailors, and her complement was increased to 52.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}} The Germans fitted her with two single {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}} anti-aircraft guns.{{sfn|Lenton|1975|p=107}} She was sunk in the port of Trieste by the [[Royal Air Force]] on 20 February 1945. ''T5'' was returned to the Royal Yugoslav navy in exile in December 1943. ''T6'' was scuttled by the Italians at [[Rimini]] on 11 September to avoid her falling into German hands. Once under German control, ''T7'' was also handed over to the Navy of the Independent State of Croatia, and served under her Yugoslav designation. Her crew came under the influence of the [[Yugoslav Partisans]], and were preparing to mutiny when the Germans intervened. She was sunk by Royal Navy MTBs off Murter Island on 25 June 1944. ''T8'' was sunk by German aircraft while under Italian control on 10 September 1944.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}}{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}}

===Post-World War II===
Only four of the original twenty-seven 250t-class torpedo boats survived World War II, two in Yugoslav service and two in Soviet service. ''Gole<U+0161>nica'' was transferred to the [[Yugoslav Navy]] after the war.{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}} She was re-armed with two {{convert|40|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns on single mounts and four {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns, and her torpedo tubes were removed. She continued in Yugoslav service under that name until October 1959, when she was taken out of service. ''T5'' was also transferred to the Yugoslav Navy after the war,{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}} and renamed ''Cer'', she was fitted with two {{convert|40|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns on single mounts and one {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}} gun. She served until 1962, when she was broken up.{{sfn|Gardiner|1983|p=388}} ''Musson'' and ''Toros'' were returned to Romania in October 1945, and stricken the following month.{{sfn|Monakov|Rohwer|2012|p=270}}

